<h3><span>METABOLISM AND ENERGY</span></h3>
<p class="">Collagen contains glycine, which is an amino acid known to form muscle tissue by converting glucose <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/glycine" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">into energy</a> to feed muscle cells. This, in turn, can help <a href="https://academic.oup.com/ajcn/article-abstract/61/5/1058/4781908" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">boost metabolism</a> and energy production. Previously mentioned, collagen is known to increase lean muscle mass, which, in turn, can give your metabolism a boost because <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/weight-loss/in-depth/metabolism/art-20046508" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">muscle burns more calories</a> than fat.</p>
